info:
This example uses a blank template with
the IIFE build of the front-end client.

It does not use any front-end framework, just
pure HTML, CSS and JavaScript.

The IIFE build should be included using a link
tag in your HTML.

name: uibuilder standard output
info:
This shows the data coming out of the
uibuilder node's Port #1 (top) which is
the standard output.

Here you will see any standard msg sent from
your front-end code.

name: uibuilder control output
info:
This shows the data coming out of the
uibuilder node's Port #2 (bottom) which is
the control output.

Here you will see any control msg either sent
by the node itself or from the front-end library.

For example the "client disconnect" and
"client connect" messages. Or the "visibility"
messages from the client.

Loop the "client connect", "cache replay" and
"cache clear" messages back to a `uib-cache`
node before the input to uibuilder in order
to control the output of the cache.

name: showMsg: Toggle Visible Msgs
info:

The display will appear as the last child of
that selected element.

e.g. `body` or `#more`.

name: Cache
info:
Cache inputs based on the msg.topic.

Just the last msg is kept for each
topic.

Default context store is used in this
example since not everyone will have
defined a file-based store.

That means that if you want an initial
zero-code layout, you need to trigger
its sending from a trigger node that
fires when Node-RED (re)starts.

name: client-tests-control-outputs
info:
Sends control messages back to the cache input

This ensures that when new clients (browser
tabs) connect or if a page is reloaded, 
the browser gets the cached data automatically.

You could filter this output to only include
"client connect" messages if you wanted to 
improve efficiency when you expect lots of 
clients to connect.

name: On Start (Heading)
info:
Runs on Node-RED startup so that the cache is always
populated even if you do not have a Node-RED persistent
context store defined.

Sets the payload for the page title, heading and
sub-heading.

Also sets a distinct msg.topic which is used by the
`uib-cache` node.

set: myvarstore (browser local storage, autoload) \n - save data to browser local storage with auto-load
info:
Sets a client managed variable `myvarstore` to an object 
AND writes it to localStorage if possible.

It also sets the autoload flag so that if the page is
reloaded by the user, the variable is restored (if possible).

WARNING: localStorage is shared between all pages/tabs 
on the same (sub)domain and port (origin).

NOTE that localStorage only survives until the browser is closed.

See [Controling from Node-RED](./uibuilder/docs/#/client-docs/control-from-node-red#set-variable)
in the docs for details.

name: Show an on-page notification (method: notify)
payload: This is a message from the payload
info:
Note that this is different to the `notification` uib command,
that shows an OS toast notification, this shows an on-page
pop-over.

The difference between this and the "alert" method is that
this does autohides by default and it has no warning icon.

Otherwise, it is the same and both use the `showDialog`
method under the skin.

name: msg._uib ...
scrollTo: Scroll to the top of the page if it isn't visible (quiet:true)
info:
The `prop` OR the `value` property can be set with the URL
to navigate to.

The URL can be:

1. A full URL (e.g. `https://example.com/somewhere`)
2. A relative URL (e.g. `./anotherpage.html`)
3. A routing hash (e.g. `#route02`)

Or a combination of (1 OR 2) and 3.

#### Relative URLs

Are relative to the CURRENT PAGE. So if that is 
`index.html`, `./page2.html` would be in the same
source folder as would `./folder` (which would move to
`./folder/index.html`).

Similarly, if on the `folder` page, `../` would move up
a level to the main index html page.

#### Routing Hashes

For pure front-end routing, using `uibrouter` or similar
library, simply send `#newroute` to move to the new route
without reloading the page.

Putting a hash on the end of a full or relative URL will
trigger the route on the resulting page load.

name: SPA navigate: Hash change (router)
info:
For pure SPA (Single Page App) front-end routing,
using the `uibrouter` or similar library,
simply send `#newroute` to move to the new route
without reloading the page.

Putting a hash on the end of a full or relative URL will
trigger the route on the resulting page load.

Hash route changes do not reload the web page.

If the page is not an SPA, nothing will happen.
